\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Schematic of the measurement setup. A grounded resistor in a copper shield connected via BNC-cable to an amplifier. The signal goes through two identical amplifiers in parallel, outputting an amplified signal in stereo which is then sent through 3.5mm cable to the laptop via an external sound card.}}{2}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:circuit}{{1}{2}{Schematic of the measurement setup. A grounded resistor in a copper shield connected via BNC-cable to an amplifier. The signal goes through two identical amplifiers in parallel, outputting an amplified signal in stereo which is then sent through 3.5mm cable to the laptop via an external sound card}{figure.1}{}}
\newlabel{eq:Gain}{{7}{2}{}{equation.0.7}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces (a) Characterization of the amplifier gain at a fixed frequency, modeled by Equation \ref {eq:Gain}. The gain data (blue) was plotted against frequency. Curve fitting (red) of the collected data produced gain $G_0=2170\pm 10$ and cutoff frequency $f_c = 9900 \pm 100$ Hz (reduced $\chi ^2=0.26$) (b) Characterization of the frequency dependence of the sound card. Sound card voltage $V_{sc}$ over input voltage $V_{in}$ was plotted against frequency (blue) and the data was interpolated (red) to create a frequency correction function.}}{2}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:Cal}{{2}{2}{(a) Characterization of the amplifier gain at a fixed frequency, modeled by Equation \ref {eq:Gain}. The gain data (blue) was plotted against frequency. Curve fitting (red) of the collected data produced gain $G_0=2170\pm 10$ and cutoff frequency $f_c = 9900 \pm 100$ Hz (reduced $\chi ^2=0.26$) (b) Characterization of the frequency dependence of the sound card. Sound card voltage $V_{sc}$ over input voltage $V_{in}$ was plotted against frequency (blue) and the data was interpolated (red) to create a frequency correction function}{figure.2}{}}
